occurrences.line_text: To whom approching, in that painefull stound
But when Briana saw that drery stound,
Next that ye Ladies ayde in euery stead and stound.
With loud laments that most vnluckie stound,
And droue away the stound, which mortally attacht him.
Therefore there still he stood as in a stound,
Both for the perill of the present stound,
His deepe compassion of her dolefull stound,
Ne cease her sorrow and impatient stound,
That hath me driuen to this drery stound.
Did slay againe, as ye may see there in the stound.
And oftentimes great grones, and grieuous stounds,
But this the sword, which wrought those cruell stounds,
With sodaine stounds of wrath and griefe attone:
And ranckling inward with vnruly stounds,
The Lyon stoup to him in lowly wise,
Should him dismay, and make him stoup so low,
He made him stoup perforce vnto his knee,
Whom Guyon seeing stoup, pursewed fast
And meekely stoup vnto the victour strong:
That forced him to stoupe vpon his knee;
His stout courage to stoupe, and shew his inward paine.
And eke he somewhat seem'd to stoupe afore
That made him stoupe, till he did him bestride:
And made them stoupe, that looked earst so hie.
She gan to stoupe, and her proud mind conuert
Who will not stoupe with good, shall be made stoupe with harme.
Who will not stoupe with good, shall be made stoupe with harme.
As a faire stoupe of her high soaring thought,
No shame to stoupe, ones head more high to reare,
That made him stoupe to ground with meeke humilitie.
Gan stoupe, and falling downe with humble awe,
From so high step to stoupe vnto so low.
Had he not stouped so, he should haue clouen bee.
Could so great courage stouped haue to ought?
And stouped oft his head from shame to shield;
Stoupes at a flying heron with proud disdaine,
Hight Humiltï¿½. They passe in stouping low;
At last low stouping with vnweldie sway,
The subtile ayre, stouping with all his might,
Crept in by stouping low, or stealing of the kaies.
And stouping downe to her in drery swound,
With many idle stoups her troubling still:
Till comming to this well, he stoupt to drincke:
Yet stoupt he not, but lay still in the wind,
And soone leaue off this toylesome wearie stoure;
The one she slew in that impatient stoure,
Which suddein fit, and halfe extatick stoure
So all together stird vp strifull stoure,
And wondred at their impacable stoure,
Against the storme of euery dreadfull stoure:
And there came Stoure with terrible aspect,
What strokes, what dreadfull stoure it stird this day:
He bad him stand, t'abide the bitter stoure
Seeing his sharpe assault and cruell stoure
And had endured many a dreadfull stoure
Amid the thickest woods. The Champion stout
He could not rest, but did his stout heart eat,
Did much emmoue his stout heroï¿½icke heart,
He was to weete a stout and sturdie thiefe,
But he was stout, and lust did now inflame
Yet the stout Faerie mongst the middest crowd
Euen stout Sans foy (O who can then refrayn?)
The Sarazin was stout, and wondrous strong,
Lo where the stout Sansioy doth sleepe in deadly shade.
Stout Scipio, and stubborne Hanniball,
And aged limbs on Cypresse stadle stout,
He led away with courage stout and bold.
The lucklesse conflict with the Gyant stout,
Full many knights aduenturous and stout
Her champion stout, and for to ayde his frend,
Of his froth-fomy steed, whose courage stout
Being arriued, where that champion stout
His stout courage to stoupe, and shew his inward paine.
Ne let thy stout hart melt in pitty vayne:
Of mightie GÃ¶emot, whom in stout fray
The auncient Abus, where with courage stout
Stout Ferrex and sterne Porrex him in prison threw.
Which seeing stout Bunduca, vp arose,
With stedfast courage and stout hardiment;
Exploits made Rome to quake, stout Guendolen,
And generous stout courage did inspire,
But when I read, how stout Debora strake
A virgin strange and stout him should dismay, or kill.
Emongst them was sterne Strife, and Anger stout,
But the stout Damzell to him leaping light,
But still with stedfast eye and courage stout
She that no lesse was courteous then stout,
And of those Knights who is most stout on ground,
Couragious Cambell, and stout Triamond,
Which whenas Cambell, that was stout and wise,
Stout Priamond, but not so strong to strike,
Strong Diamond, but not so stout a knight,
But Triamond was stout and strong alike:
Their days mote be abridged through their corage stout.
But with stout courage turnd vpon them all,
That was to weet, the stout Sir Sangliere,
By his sole manhood and atchieuement stout
Tempred with sternesse and stout maiestie,
In greater perils to be stout and bold,
Resolu'd him to assault with manhood stout,
Stout Theseus, and Pirithous his feare;
Ne storming Humber, though he looked stout;
Cymodoce, and stout Autonoe,
But if through stout disdaine of manly mind,
But like a rebell stout I will him vse.
In which stout Britomart her selfe did rest,
Which Britomart withstood with courage stout,
Yet neither Ino, nor Medea stout,
All which he did assault with courage stout,
To weet a wicked villaine, bold and stout,
And forced them, how euer strong and stout
Nathlesse thereto he was full stout and tall,
Faire gentle swayne, and yet as stout as fayre,
But stout Despetto in his greater pryde,
And laying yet a fresh with courage stout
But the stout Prince, with much more steddy stowre
Threatning to yoke them tow & tame their corage stout.
And entertayning them with courage stout,
And yield it those, that stouter could it wield:
And he the stoutest knight, that euer wonne?
That stoutest heart, I weene, could cause to quake.
In stoutest minds, and maketh monstrous warre;
That could the stoutest courage haue appald;
They by consent should chose the stoutest three,
So stoutest knights doen oftentimes in field.
Of Aspes sting her selfe did stoutly kill:
And double blowes about him stoutly laid,
But Trompart stoutly stayd to taken heed,
And standing stoutly vp, his loftie crest
And stoutly prou'd thy puissaunce here in sight;
So stoutly he withstood their strong assay,
The walles so stoutly with their sturdie maine,
With her on foot, and stoutly forward came;
But stoutly dealt his blowes, and euery way
Shall stoutly him defeat, and thousand Saxons kill.
Stoutly forth stepping on the further shore,
And stoutly came vnto the Castle gate;
Yet nought dismayd, them stoutly well withstood;
Doth in defence thereof full stoutly stond:
Against him stoutly ran, as nought afeard,
Which had himselfe so stoutly well acquit;
That with great rage he stoutly doth denay;
And cruell spoyle, which he had spard, to stow:
The headlesse tronke, as heedlesse of that stower,
The euill stownd, that daungerd her estate,
For till that stownd could neuer wight him harme,
That bitter stownd, but turning quicke aside
For whose deare sake full many a bitter stownd,
And eke the Redcrosse knight ran to the stownd,
And his sweete lips, on which before that stownd
And reskewed out of the heauy stownd.
Ne in that stownd wist, how her selfe to beare;
The perilous present stownd, in which their liues were set.
Then gan she waile and weepe, to see that woefull stowre.
She has forgot, how many a wofull stowre
And for his sake haue felt full many an heauie stowre.
But he was wary of that deadly stowre,
Which haue endured many a dreadfull stowre,
And staggering steps, to weet, what suddein stowre
And he that harrowd hell with heauie stowre,
In mind to marke the beast. At which sad stowre,
T'auoide the rash assault and wrathfull stowre
And wisely watch to ward that deadly stowre:
Which oft the Paynim sau'd from deadly stowre.
That nothing may withstand his stormy stowre,
First did it shew the bitter balefull stowre,
But with hart-thrilling throbs and bitter stowre,
I haue beene trained vp in warlike stowre,
From the worlds end, through many a bitter stowre:
Her clowdy care into a wrathfull stowre,
But to auoyde th'intollerable stowre,
They felt, could once sustaine the hideous stowre,
And shrowd their persons from that stormie stowre.
But thus turmoild from one to other stowre,
He gan record the lamentable stowre,
Vnto the crooke t'abide the balefull stowre,
As being troubled with that stormy stowre;
Great ruth through her misfortunes tragicke stowre;
To stirre vp strife, and many a Tragicke stowre,
But the stout Prince, with much more steddy stowre
And lastly throwne themselues into these heauy stowres.
But straggling plots, which to and fro do ronne
Which when that warriour heard, dismounting straict
And many yeares throughout the world I straid,
Me litle needed from my right way to haue straid.
For I vnwares this way by fortune straid,
And looking after long, did marke which way she straid.
And seeking long, to weet which way she straid
Whose right she is, where euer she be straide,
Much can they prayse the trees so straight and hy,
The God obayde, and calling forth straight way
Whose sences all were straight benumbd and starke.
Haue slaine him straight: but when he sees his age,
From surging gulf two monsters straight were brought,
Straight he vpstarted from the loathed layes,
Which straight to her was yeelded without let.
Which straight flew ope, and gaue her way to ride.
Whom straight the Prince ensuing, in together far'd.
Commaunding Proteus straight t'enlarge the mayd,
Departed straight to Proteus therewithall:
Commaunded straight his armour to be brought,
And mounting straight vpon a charret hye,
The Damzell straight went, as she was directed,
She gladly graunted it: then he straight way
Fell straight about their neckes, as they did kneele,
And stopt the bleeding straight, ere he it staunched thought.
The warrant straight was made, and therewithall
She straightly straynd, and colled tenderly,
The one in hand an yron whip did straine,
His brawnie armes, and all his body straine,
Which after her his nimble wings doth straine,
A forrest bill, which both his hands did straine;
Twixt both his hands few sparkes he close did straine,
With that the darts which his right hand did straine,
Sprung of the auncient stocke of Princes straine,
Did cast about by sleight the truth thereout to straine.
To sharpen him, and their owne cursed tongs did straine.
So nigh at hand, nor force his shield to straine,
And threatning his sharpe clawes, now wanting powre to straine.
Who when they heard that pitteous strained voice,
But strained him so streightly, that he chokt him neare.
That with the straint his wesand nigh he brast.
Attacht that faitor false, and bound him strait:
He brought him through a darksome narrow strait,
And with so'exceeding furie at him strake,
Whose right haunch earst my stedfast arrow strake?
But when I read, how stout Debora strake
That almost in the backe he oft her strake:
But with his heeles so sorely he him strake,
And gainst the cold hard earth so sore him strake,
His burning eyen, whom bloudie strakes did staine,
Drunke vp his life; his corse left on the strand.
Forthwith directed to that further strand;
Did thrust the shallop from the floting strand:
And all the way him followd on the strand,
Of Scots and English both, that tyned on his strand.
He smote it off, that tumbling on the strand
But for this threasure throwne vppon his strand;
Or fell Medea, when on Colchicke strand
He had not passed farre vpon the strand,
Was for to seeke aduenture in strange place,
That to strange knight no better countenance allowd.
Had wrought that horror strange, and dar'd his dreaded powre.
And trembling with strange feare, did like an earthquake show.
Of tydings strange, and of aduentures rare:
Strange thing it is an errant knight to see
By strange occasion she did him behold,
Though strange beginning had, yet fixed is
And writing strange characters in the ground,
And diuerse plots did frame, to maske in strange disguise.
A virgin strange and stout him should dismay, or kill.
And wandred in the world in strange aray,
That suddein change she strange aduenture thought.
And merueild at his strange intendiment;
Then since that strange Knights loue from him was quitted,
Some, that it was a maske of strange disguise:
And strange aduentures, all the way they rode:
For that strange Dame, whose beauties wonderment
The hard aduentures and strange haps to tell;
But like strange wight, whom he had seene no where,
Strange was her tyre; for on her head a crowne
He wore, that seemed strange to common vew,
But that strange Knight, the fairer loue to gaine,
All that behold so strange prodigious sight,
With his strange weapon, neuer wont in warre,
Strange were the words in Britomartis eare;
Where shee strange visions sees:
Through great astonishment of that strange sight;
In cyphers strange, that few could rightly read,
Those two strange knights were to her presence brought;
Those two strange knights such homage to her make,
And eke her selfe through sudden strange affright,
In these strange waies, where neuer foote did vse,
In perils strange, in labours long and wide;
And much more strangely gan to loue his sight,
Great pleasure had those stranger knights, to see
Fiercely that stranger forward came, and nigh
I saw (quoth she) a stranger knight, whose name
A stranger knight, that did his glorie shend:
That all those stranger knights full sore agrieued,
About the house, at sent of stranger guest:
This other day (sayd he) a stranger knight
A stranger knight, sayd he, vnknowne by name,
Then for that stranger knight they loud did call,
Goe thou vnto that stranger Faery Knight,
When these two stranger knights arriu'd in place,
That he should be so sterne to stranger wight:
A stranger wight in place, her plaint she stayd,
That she did loue a stranger swayne then him more dere.
And eke all strangers in that region
A cruell carle, the which all strangers slew,
Vnto a strangers loue so lightly placed,
Strangers no more so rudely to intreat,
Strangle her, else she sure will strangle thee.
Strangle her, else she sure will strangle thee.
That stratageme had oftentimes assayd
Vntill a nation straung, with visage swart,
Of straunge aduentures, which abroad did pas.
Of a straunge man I can you tidings tell,
Yet musing at the straunge occasion,
By straunge aduenture as it did betyde,
And far abroad for straunge aduentures sought:
Straunge Lady, in so straunge habiliment,
Straunge Lady, in so straunge habiliment,
Of straunge aduentures, and of perils sad,
The tydings straunge did him abashed make,
Out of my way, through perils straunge and hard;
Such is this well, wrought by occasion straunge,
How in that place straunge knight arriued late,
Straunge sort of fight, three valiaunt knights to see
Resort, to heare of straunge aduentures to be told.
Straunge seemed to the knight, that aye with foe
Yet neuer in this straunge astonishment.
The antique shapes of kings and kesars straunge & rare.
How that straunge sword refusd, to serue his need,
Which that straunge knight for him sustained had,
How may straunge knight hope euer to aspire,
What straunge aduenture do ye now pursew?
All threatning death, all in straunge manner armd,
For neuer had they seene so straunge a sight.
Straunge was her tyre, and all her garment blew,
He sent to Germanie, straunge aid to reare,
Deformed creatures, in straunge difference,
Vnweeting, what such horrour straunge did reare.
His treble, a straunge kinde of harmony;
And straunge phantomes doth let vs oft forsee,
Whom straunge aduenture did from Britaine fet,
(For she her sexe vnder that straunge purport
And many straunge aduentures to be fond,
But this affection nothing straunge I find;
So straungely vewed her straunge louers shade,
Forthwith themselues disguising both in straunge
Strongly the straunge knight ran, and sturdily
His vncouth shield and straunge armes her dismayd,
For of her errour straunge I haue great ruth and mone.
By what straunge accident faire Chrysogone
So straunge ensample of conception;
That in so straunge disguizement there did maske,
Driuen to great distresse by Fortune straunge,
Malbecco will no straunge knights host,
Of straunge affaires, and noble hardiment,
In straunge disguize, to slake his scalding smart;
Straunge thing it seem'd, that none was to possesse
In full straunge notes was sweetly heard to sound,
In a discolour'd cote, of straunge disguyse,
Straunge horrour, to deforme his griesly shade;
Figuring straunge characters of his art,
One in a charet of straunge furniment,
Attyr'd in forraine armes and straunge aray:
He saw his senses straunge astonishment,
Gan cast a secret liking to this captiue straunge.
Whose life and manners straunge she neuer knew;
Kept himselfe still in his straunge armour dight.
A straunge aduenture, which not farre thence lay;
Made of straunge stuffe, but all to worne and ragged,
And with their brightnesse daz'd the straunge beholders eye.
Straunge there to see, it did them much amaze,
By straunge occasion, that here needs forth be set.
It is most straunge and wonderfull to fynd
Which a straunge knight, that neare afore him went,
Vnto a straunge mischaunce, that menac'd her decay.
But what straunge fortunes vnto him befell,
Much wondred Calidore at this straunge sight,
She should it cause be fostred vnder straunge attyre.
Tho wondring long at those so straunge euents,
Straunge bands, whose like till then he neuer bore,
So straungely passioned, and to her gently sayd,
So straungely vewed her straunge louers shade,
That who so straungely had him seene bestad,
Vpon checklaton he was straungely dight,
To weet what end to straunger knights may fall.
That straunger knight his name and nation tell;
The noyse thereof calth forth that straunger knight,
But yielded had to that same straunger knight:
A straunger in thy home, and ignoraunt
By this that straunger knight in presence came,
Besiegd of many foes, whom straunger
Abasht, that her a straunger did avise:
These straunger knights through passing, forth were led
Vntill a straunger king from vnknowne soyle
And eke that straunger knight emongst the rest;
To giust with that braue straunger knight a cast,
And seeing him behind a straunger knight,
A straunger knight, from whence no man could reed,
The third dayes prize vnto that straunger Knight,
The stone, which passed straunger at him threw;
That was a straunger to her wretched case;
By a faire Lady, and a straunger Knight,
Then thus said he, There is a straunger knight,
Whereat much grieu'd against that straunger knight,
Him to betray vnto a straunger swaine:
But forth in hast ran to the straunger Mayd;
Themselues to setten forth to straungers sight:
Those pretious hils from straungers enuious sight,
But at these straungers presence euery one did hush.
It was her guise, all Straungers goodly so to greet.
That they as Straungers shalbe notifide.
And slacke attendaunce vnto straungers call.
For yeelding to a straungers loue so light,
And straungers to deuoure, which on their border
He much was troubled at that straungers guize,
To the greene wood, to gather strawberies,
Let him lodge hard, and lie in strawen bed,
Some plaid with strawes, some idly sat at ease;
No more then for the stroke of strawes or bents:
When weening to returne, whence they did stray,
I saw before mine eyes, if I were knowne to stray.
And that in endlesse error she might euer stray.
The further he doth goe, the further he doth stray.
Then do no further goe, no further stray,
Or doen thy feeble feet vnweeting hither stray?
Or gan to shrinke, or from the right to stray,
And suffred not in wrath his hastie steps to stray.
And stray in perilous gulfe, her dwelling is:
Did out of order stray about her daintie eares.
The sea is wide, and easie for to stray;
Amid th'AegÃ¦an sea long time did stray,
And as he through the wandring wood did stray,
Suffring my hand against my heart to stray:
Disdaine and Scorne, I through the world should stray,
In wildernesse and wastfull deserts strayd,
I lately traueild, that vnwares I strayd
Whose hastie hand so farre from reason strayd,
The traine whereof loose far behind her strayd,
But to and fro at disauenture strayd;
Eftsoones his warlike courser, which was strayd
And in her litle loues stead, which was strayd,
And yet three yeares I now abroad haue strayd,
For yet she may be safe though somewhat strayd;
With siluer streames amongst the linnen stray'd;
Your brothers threasure, which from him is strayd,
As by the way vnweetingly I strayd,
The good Sir Calepine, that farre was strayd,
To seeke her strayed Champion, if she might attaine.
As when a wearie traueller that strayes
Straying alone withouten groome or guide;
She straightly straynd, and colled tenderly,
Sometimes a thwart, sometimes he strooke him strayt,
Would him haue rent in thousand peeces strayt:
The knight was ruled, and the Boateman strayt
And not well fastened, would not strike him strayt,
Laide heauy hands on him, and held so strayte,
A streame of cole black bloud forth gushed fro[m]; her corse.
Thereby a Christall streame did gently play,
A trickling streame from high rocke tumbling downe
But who can turne the streame of destinee,
Drunke of the streame, as cleare as cristall glas;
Forth gushed, like fresh water streame from riuen rocke.
The streame thereof would driue a water-mill.
A trickling streame of Balme, most soueraine
To tell, were as to striue against the streame.
A gentle streame, whose murmuring waue did play
Vnto the mightie streame him to betake,
A downe the streame, and all his vowes make vaine,
Where streame more violent and greedy growes:
And a large streame of bloud out of the wound did flow.
The carkas with the streame was carried downe,
And saw his drouer driue along the streame,
And from their nosethrilles blow the brynie streame,
A streame of coleblacke bloud thence gusht amaine,
The whiles his life ran foorth in bloudie streame,
Of a fresh streame I with that Elfe did play,
Ten thousand fishes play, and decke his pleasant streame.
And Conway which out of his streame doth send
But the streame washt away her guilty blood.
Like as a water streame, whose swelling sourse
And streames of purple bloud new dies the verdant fields.
In tender flesh, that streames of bloud down flow,
Large streames of bloud out of the truncked stocke
Welling out streames of teares, and quite dismayd
As from two weeping eyes, fresh streames do flow,
And Titan playing on the eastern streames,
At the well head the purest streames arise:
Infinit streames continually did well
And through the persant aire shoote forth their azure streames.
Out of their brests, that streames of bloud did rayle
Thence streames of purple bloud issuing rife,
That streames of bloud his armour all bedide.
From his moist eies, and like two streames procead;
Pouring out streames of poyson and of gall
Shooting forth farre away two flaming streames,
With siluer streames amongst the linnen stray'd;
And Tygris fierce, whose streames of none may be withstood.
The Churne, and Charwell, two small streames, which   pained
Both thirty sorts of fish, and thirty sundry streames.
And here and there shooting forth siluer streames,
When he beheld the streames of purple blood
With streames of bloud; which tracting by the traile,
Like many water streames, a while she stayd;
For in her streaming blood he did embay
Through many a stroke, & many a streaming wound,
That when the Paynim spyde the streaming blood,
Doth groueling fall, and with his streaming gore
And with their garments strowes the paued street:
So him they led through all their streetes along,
Who streight him rent in thousand peeces small,
Which when the wakeful Elfe perceiu'd, streight way
And streight deliuered to a Faery knight,
So vp he rose, and thence amounted streight.
